Microservices is an architectural style where an application is divided into small independent services, 
each responsible for a specific functionality. These services communicate via REST APIs or messaging systems like Kafka. 
It provides scalability, flexibility, and independent deployment.

------api gateway-----------
API Gateway acts as a single entry point for all client requests in a microservices architecture. 
It handles routing, authentication, load balancing, and logging, reducing complexity for clients and centralizing cross-cutting concerns
Client sends request to API Gateway, which routes it to the appropriate service like Order or Payment. 
In some cases, services communicate directly with each other without going through the gateway. Authentication is handled using JWT, 
often integrated with OAuth for authorization. Different API Gateway implementations like Spring Cloud Gateway or Zuul can be used.

------eureka & service discovery -----------
Eureka is a service discovery mechanism where services register themselves with a Eureka Server. 
Each microservice acts as a Eureka client. Instead of hardcoding service URLs, services can discover
and communicate with each other dynamically using the service name.

-----------circuitbreaker and resilence4j-----------------
Circuit Breaker is used to stop repeated calls to a failing service. When failures exceed a threshold,
the circuit opens and calls are blocked. After some time, it allows limited requests in half-open state to
check recovery. It improves system resilience and prevents cascading failures.
@CircuitBreaker(name = "paymentService", fallbackMethod = "fallback")
public String callPayment() {
    return restTemplate.getForObject("http://PAYMENT-SERVICE/pay", String.class);
}

public String fallback(Exception e) {
    return "Payment service is down";
}
